<!doctype html><html><head><meta charset="utf-8"><title>H38-T002 Project Packet</title><style>body{font-family:Arial,sans-serif;line-height:1.45;color:#111827}h1{color:#0f172a}h2{border-bottom:1px solid #cbd5e1;padding-bottom:4px}table{border-collapse:collapse;width:100%;margin:12px 0}td,th{border:1px solid #cbd5e1;padding:8px;vertical-align:top}th{background:#e2e8f0}.phase{background:#f8fafc;border-left:5px solid #0ea5e9;padding:10px;margin:12px 0}.small{font-size:12px;color:#475569}</style></head><body><h1>Highway 38 Solutions - Project Packet</h1><p><b>Sample ID:</b> H38-T002<br><b>Package:</b> Project Packet<br><b>Scenario:</b> 28x40 garage idea to layout and build order</p><p><img src="../assets/sample-garage-proof.svg" alt="Garage project visual" style="width:100%;max-width:760px"></p><h2>Customer input received</h2><ul><li>Outside dimension: 28 ft x 40 ft.</li><li>Two overhead doors on short side with space between doors and about 2 ft to corners.</li><li>Uses: vehicle parking, workbench, tool storage, seasonal storage, small project work.</li><li>Customer wants a practical order before buying storage or cabinets.</li></ul><h2>Zone plan</h2><table><tr><th>Zone</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Placement rule</th><th>Do first</th></tr><tr><td>Vehicle lane</td><td>Keep one vehicle bay usable.</td><td>Starts at overhead door and stays clear.</td><td>Mark clear lane before moving storage.</td></tr><tr><td>Workbench zone</td><td>Repair, assembly, layout, small jobs.</td><td>Near power and daily tools.</td><td>Measure outlet locations and walking clearance.</td></tr><tr><td>Wall storage</td><td>Seasonal storage, parts, bins, long items.</td><td>Keep off floor where possible.</td><td>Choose wall rail or shelving after dimensions.</td></tr><tr><td>Dirty work zone</td><td>Grinding, cutting, messy repair.</td><td>Away from clean storage and parked vehicle.</td><td>Mark safe distance and ventilation concern.</td></tr></table><h2>Build order</h2><div class="phase"><b>Phase 1 - Confirm:</b> measure wall lengths, ceiling height, overhead door tracks, outlets, lights, and heater clearance.</div><div class="phase"><b>Phase 2 - Clear:</b> create vehicle lane, temporary sort zone, trash pile, keep pile, and unknown pile.</div><div class="phase"><b>Phase 3 - Install:</b> wall rail/shelving, daily tool zone, parts staging shelf, labels.</div><div class="phase"><b>Phase 4 - Upgrade later:</b> lighting, heat, cabinets, compressed air, better workbench, dust/dirty work separation.</div><h2>Material groups</h2><table><tr><th>Group</th><th>Examples</th><th>Buy now?</th></tr><tr><td>Measurement/layout</td><td>Tape, painter tape, marker, graph paper, labels.</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Storage</td><td>Wall rails, hooks, shelving, labeled totes.</td><td>After measurements</td></tr><tr><td>Workbench</td><td>Bench top, legs/base, power strip, task light.</td><td>After parking lane is confirmed</td></tr><tr><td>Later upgrades</td><td>Cabinets, lighting, heater, air lines.</td><td>No, not first spend</td></tr></table><h2>Customer-ready summary</h2><p>Your garage problem is not a full remodel yet. The correct first win is to protect a vehicle lane, assign storage zones, and delay expensive cabinets until the wall and ceiling measurements are confirmed.</p><p class="small">Highway 38 Solutions - Big problems. Clear plans. Hypothetical sample deliverable.</p></body></html>